
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `lsof` baraye list kardan hameye file-haye baz shode (open files) estefade mishavad. In dastoor be shoma komak mikonad bebinid kodam process-ha kodam file-ha ya socket-ha ra baz kardeand.  

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `lsof -i`  --> 🌐 List kardan etesalate shabake (network connections).  
    🔹 `lsof -p PID`  --> 🔍 List kardan file-haye baz shode baraye process ba ID (PID) moshakhas. Be jaye PID, shomare ID process ra benevisid.  
    🔹 `lsof | grep FILENAME` --> 📁 Peyda kardan process-haee ke file (FILENAME) khasi ra baz kardeand.  
    🔹 `lsof -u USERNAME` --> 👤 List kardan file-haye baz shode baraye karbar (USER) moshakhas.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ lsof
    
    🔹 Namayesh hameye file-haye baz shode dar system.

    $ lsof -i :80
    
    🔹 Namayesh hameye process-haee ke be port 80 gosh midahand.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ lsof -p 1234
    
    🔹 List kardan hameye file-haye baz shode tavasote process ba ID 1234.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `lsof` command is used to list all open files. This command helps you see which processes have which files or sockets open.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `lsof -i`  --> 🌐 List network connections.
    🔹 `lsof -p PID`  --> 🔍 List open files for a specific process ID (PID). Replace PID with the actual process ID number.
    🔹 `lsof | grep FILENAME` --> 📁 Find processes that have a specific file (FILENAME) open.
    🔹 `lsof -u USERNAME` --> 👤 List open files for a specific user (USER).

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ lsof
    
    🔹 Show all open files on the system.

    $ lsof -i :80
    
    🔹 Show all processes listening on port 80.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ lsof -p 1234
    
    🔹 List all open files by the process with ID 1234.
